:"1317","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Poulton, Wiltshire, England":"Poulton, Wiltshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England":"Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Goddard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from <i>Godhard</i>, a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The name was popular in Europe during the Middle Ages as a result of the fame of Saint Gotthard, an 11th-century bishop of Hildesheim who founded a hospice on the pass from Switzerland to Italy that bears his name. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","English: perhaps occasionally a variant of the occupational name   Gothard  . The two surnames may have been much confused.","French: variant of   Godard  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Gothard","meanings":["English: variant of   Goddard  .","English: occupational name for a keeper of goats, from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> (Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>hierde</i>) ‘herdsman, keeper’.","English: variant of <b>Goater</b>, with excrescent <i>-d</i>, either a topographic name for someone who lived by a stream or ditch, from Middle English <i>gote</i> ‘watercourse’ + the agent suffix <i>-(e)r</i>, or an occupational name either from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> ‘goatherd’ or from Middle English <i>goter</i> ‘goatherd’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>got(e)</i> ‘goat’ (Old English <i>gāt</i>)."]},{"name":"Godard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Reynald, Alcide, Armand, Aurel, Celine, Cyprien, Dominique, Emile, Etienne, Euclide, Gilles.","French: from the personal name <i>Godard</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Goddard  ).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Goddard  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Goertz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Christoph, Erwin, Guenter, Juergen, Kurt, Otto.","German (also <b>Görtz</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Goert</i>, a short form of <i>Godhard</i> (see   Goddard  ),   Gottfried   or   Gerhardt  , common in Rhineland.","Germanized form (also <b>Görtz</b>) of Sorbian <b>Gerc</b>; see   Gertz  ."]},{"name":"Goodart","meanings":["English: variant of   Goddard  .","Perhaps also an Americanized form of German   Gothard  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":12,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":21,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John Goddard II was born about 1316, in Aldbourne, Wiltshire, England, his father, John Goddard I, was 48 and his mother, Alice Elizabeth Tettersell, was 38. He had at least 1 son with Hannah Seaver. He died about 138